# Component Styling And Class Naming

- When adding or updating UI code, prefer styling through existing component root selectors and nested CSS rather than inventing new class names for specificity.
- Do not create long one-off class names whose only purpose is to target a single element for styling.
- Add a new class only when it represents a real semantic or reusable element in the component structure.
- When a component already has a root class, use that root plus nested selectors as the first approach for styling related children.
- Prefer a normal root class for the component, then short nested child classes with a leading underscore like `._panel`, `._trigger`, or `._day`.
- Reserve longer non-underscored child class names for cases that are intentionally global or portaled outside the component root.
- When editing an existing component, treat nearby naming-pattern violations as cleanup candidates instead of copying them forward.
- If a touched component already uses BEM-style modifiers, unnested child selectors, or long one-off class names that can be safely normalized with low churn, clean them up in the same change.
- Do not follow an existing local violation just for consistency with that file.
- Keep cleanup tightly scoped to the component you are already editing.

## Preferred

```tsx
<div class="profile-drawer">
  <Tooltip content="...">
    <IconButton class="_regenerate" />
  </Tooltip>
</div>
```

```css
.profile-drawer {
  ._regenerate {
    position: absolute;
  }
}
```

## Avoid

```tsx
<div class="profile-drawer">
  <IconButton class="profile-drawer-avatar-regenerate-button" />
</div>
```
